{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":24391,"record_hash":"sha256:1cd0a825c02cbb70880884fb327c0bc734618baf7c84707489e8a7a386fac61f","timestamp":"2026-05-11T09:15:13.994Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yes. The better shape is to stop using the transcript list as the dedupe index.\n\nRight now we do this:\n\n```text\nread :transcript list\nparse every envelope\ncollect record_hash\nfilter new records\nwrite transcript list back\n```\n\nFor this session, that means every hook capture reads/parses ~50MB just to answer “have I seen this record hash?”\n\nA better POC-sized approach is:\n\n```text\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:record-hashes = set<sha256:...>\ngitbutler:agent-session:<session-key>:transcript = list<TranscriptRecord>\n```\n\nThen capture can read the hash set, not the transcript list. For your current session that’s roughly “24k small hashes” instead of “24k full JSON envelopes with tool output”. The set is redundant data, but it earns its keep as an index.\n\nThe best version would be a GitMeta API that can atomically do:\n\n```text\nappend these transcript list entries\nadd these record hashes to the set\n```\n\nThat avoids inconsistency if a process dies between writing the transcript and writing the hash index. Without that, we’d need to choose between small-but-not-perfect app code or rebuilding the set from the transcript when missing, which is that “scar tissue” smell we’ve been pruning.\n\nMy recommendation:\n\n1. Add back `:record-hashes` as a compact dedupe index.\n2. Add a small GitMeta operation for “append list entries and add set members in one transaction” if the library shape allows it cleanly.\n3. Keep the transcript list as the canonical readable data for future handoff/review use cases.\n4. Do not jump yet to byte-offset incremental parsing. That’s faster, but it adds partial-line and rewrite/truncation complexity too early.\n\nThis would reduce hook-time work a lot without changing the external data model much.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T09:15:13.994Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}